					.chapter-number 05
					h2.chapter-title The Princess
				.chapter-text
					p During the shooting of Secret pople, where Audrey was playing a role of ballerina, she was spotted by director William Wyler. He was producing a film #[em Roman Holiday] and he felt the innocence and elfin beauty of Audrey Hepburn would make a perfect choice for the English Princess, who spends a day in Rome in the company of Gregory Peck. The film was a great hit and on the advertising Audrey Hepburn was given the same billing as Gregory Peck. In many respects, Audrey outshone her more illustrious lead Gregory Peck; as Peck predicted, it was Audrey who would be given an Oscar for her performance.
			.blockquote-container
				blockquote.blockquote
					span.blockquote-line Your heart just breaks, that’s all. But you can’t judge, or point fingers.
					span.blockquote-line You just have to be lucky enough to find someone who appreciates you.
			section.chapter
				.chapter-heading
					.chapter-number 06
					h2.chapter-title The First Love
				.chapter-text
					p Following her success in Roman Holiday, Hepburn starred in Billy Wilder's romantic Cinderella-story comedy #[em Sabrina], in which wealthy brothers (Humphrey Bogart and William Holden) compete for the affections of their chauffeur's innocent daughter (Hepburn). The actress earned herself another Academy Award nomination for her role in the film—and also landed in a deep love affair with her co-star.
					p Even though Holden was 11 years her senior with a wife and three kids, Hepburn was deeply in love and desperately wanted marriage and children. After learning that Holden had undergone a vasectomy, Hepburn officially put an end to their relationship.
