			section.chapter
				.chapter-heading
					.chapter-number 07
					h2.chapter-title The Style Icon
				.chapter-text
					p Audrey has become a worldwide symbol of style and elegance and the most ingenious quality about her sense of style is that she knew what looked good on her and what didn't. She's known for her simplicity and avoided fashion trends. She was featured on 7 September 1953 cover of TIME magazine, and also became noted for her personal style.
					p It was #[em Sabrina] movie that solidified her 40-year iconic relationship with French fashion designer, Hubert de Givenchy. Beginning in 1956, Audrey was perfectly outfitted from head to toe personally and professionally by the master couturier. Givenchy dressed Audrey in #[em Roman Holiday], #[em Breakfast at Tiffany’s], #[em Charade], and #[em My Fair Lady]. He also designed her beautiful hats and created a fragrance for her, an early celebrity collaboration.
			.blockquote-container
				blockquote.blockquote
					span.blockquote-line If I get married,
					span.blockquote-line &nbsp;I want to be very married.
			section.chapter
				.chapter-heading
					.chapter-number 08
					h2.chapter-title The Mother
				.chapter-text
					p Audrey's biggest dream of being mother became reality soon after her break-up with William Holden. Audrey met her first husband, the actor Mel Ferrer at a cocktail party hosted by mutual friend Gregory Peck. The meeting led them to collaborate in Ondine, during which they began a relationship. Eight months later they got married while preparing to star together in the film #[em War and Peace]. Their son, Sean Hepburn Ferrer, was born on 17 July 1960.
					p 14 years later, soon after divorcing Ferrer Hepburn met her second husband, Italian psychiatrist Andrea Dotti, on a Mediterranean cruise with friends in June 1968. They married in 6 month, and their son Luca Dotti was born a year after. This marriage lasted thirteen years and was dissolved in 1982.
